pr_review_body:
@samuelcolvin, please beware that this PR introduces a breaking change

This was previously a valid usecase, but with these changes it will raise an error because second positional argument is now always passed to `getter_dict`:
```py
def test_custom_getter_dict():
    class TestCls:
        x = 1
        y = 2

    def custom_getter_dict(obj):
        assert isinstance(obj, TestCls)
        return {'x': 42, 'y': 24}

    class Model(BaseModel):
        x: int
        y: int
        class Config:
            orm_mode = True
            getter_dict = custom_getter_dict
    model = Model.from_orm(TestCls())
    assert model.dict() == {'x': 42, 'y': 24}
```

After many many rounds of thought to this and going deep into what each field does, I think what we want is basically the existing `ListRelation` (I'm not sure why it didnt work when we implemented it).

We basically want something like:

```json
{
  nested_array: [
    {language: en},
    {language: es}
  ]
}
```

coming from a relation like:

```python
relations = RelationsField(
  language=PKListRelation(
    key='nested_array',
    relation_field='language'
  )
)
```

In our case they are resolved by PID, so instead of `PKListRelation(ListRelation, PKRelation)` it would be `PIDListRelation(ListRelation, PIDRelation):`.

@codewithnick Well done 🔥 
I comment on some minor issues.
Please address them, after that we will merge this PR 🚀

> I think it's good to decouple from Host but it's odd that we need this extra object to manage the closing especially when Provider has a close method!

Agreed! The extra Close will cause some confusion. Should I call Provider.Close or the returned Close.

> an alternative would be to change Host.Provider to return a shim object that forwards everything to the normal provider object except Close which it would forward to Host.CloseProvider, or going one further removing that method and just having its close logic be a private detail of this shim providers close method. Sounds cleaner, but much larger change than this.

Another option is: ProviderFactory doesn't return an io.Closer, just a Provider.
ProviderFactoryFromHost, which adapts a host to this interface, decorates the returned Provider with this shim, leaving the actual host.Provider implementation unchanged.

```go
type hostManagedProvider struct {
  plugin.Provider

  host  plugin.Host
}

func (p *hostManagedProvider) Close() error {
  p.host.CloseProvider(p.Provider)
}

func ProviderFactoryFromHost(host plugin.Host) ProviderFactory {
  return func(pkg tokens.Package, version *semver.Version) (plugin.Provider, io.Closer, error) {
    provider, err := ...
    if err != nil { ... }
    return &hostManagedProvider{Provider: provider, host: host}, nil
  }
}
```

Thank you for this @KushalBeniwal ! 

That failing check is definitely not related - a bunch of the latest PRs are failing so we'll work that out - but this PR is good to go!

@jonboiser should we merge this to 0.14.x instead of develop since we'll merge it forward soon enough?

I wonder if we need to scope this to "sub-executions only"... if that is the safer change to make.

This change as-is might could be a can of worms for accidentally combining multiple traces together.

```python
with tracer.trace("root") as root:
    thread.Thread(target, (root.context.clone(), ))


class Context:
    def clone(self):
        return Context(self.trace_id, self.span_id, _sub_context=True)
```

This is a silly example, but maybe illustrates what I mean?

